segments.text: my direction and we have so far identified the processes how to do it when we were talking about doing this comprehensive planning process we also were wanting to have this whole process endorsed by the Planning Commission and by the City Council
So we went through a long and tedious course of getting a resolution out of the city council.

The city council has finally signed a resolution endorsing our process, but given us a mandate to produce a document, what we call planning policy manual, identifying why we're doing it, how we're doing it,
with what kind of help, and it's a very detailed piece of document.
This piece of document was sent to the Planning Commission for approval.
And also in, I think January of 87, we've gotten the approval from the Planning Commission.
So here's a copy for your review.
I thank you.
So the process now is that the Planning Department will do the
sector plan.
There will be about 23 sectors identified for areas inside the city limit, outside the city limit, into the ETJ.
Really, in our sector division, the city limit is rather transparent because we feel like that really has not that much control over how development should happen.
We sort of negated that.
And also, Houston's taken a pretty forthright stand with regard to development in the ETJ, too, historically.
Yes.
Recently, we had a little bit more teeth.
I think the last legislature provided us with plaque review power.
Ephraim keeps saying that if any commissioner
county judge that would locate a development outside of the city limit in there.
In our ETJ, without the planning department's approval, we can bring lawsuits and it's really a misdemeanor offense according to the legislation.
One thing I wanted to mention, Joe, was your neighborhood planning areas are the immediate
in town areas surrounding the CBD.
That's correct.
That's usually the case when you talk about community development areas, mostly in the older neighborhoods surrounding the CBD, so to speak.
However, we did identify the CBD itself as a part of the sector planning process.
Part of the reason is there is not enough residents in that area to be included into the CD eligible
situation.
Who is in charge of the C.D.
areas?
Roberta Burroughs, another assistant director.
Okay.
I want to give her credit, too.
Yes.
Roberta, you know, you know Roberta, who is now the chapter, state chapter's, is she president or vice president or something?
One of the officers.
Well, one of the officers.
And there you have your comprehensive planning process.
Well, that's part of the summary that I was looking for just now for you.
If you want to, we can read through it quickly, or you can go back and write it out from what I gave you later on.
Well, we can get a summary, and then I can refer to that.
So we are now in the process, as you see the other map, there's sector lines drawn and there's 23 sectors identified.
We have also a report for sector boundary plan.
Somewhere along the line, the question was raised that whether the department was arbitrarily drawing some lines to divide them up into sectors.
and we have made a report and distributed it to the various groups for review and we did have some rather legitimate comments that would cause us to maybe change some of the sector lines.
We do not want to divide neighborhoods and things like that.

Well, when you say under your comprehensive planning documents that you're going to have neighborhood plans, sector plans, and summary plans, for example, what do you mean when you say neighborhood plans?
What kind of plans?
There will be elements there, won't there, of plans?
Yes, neighborhood plans will be the plans that will be within the city area first.
Location-wise, that is a specific item.
Well, like what?
For example, Fourth Ward.
Okay, but what kind of, what will the plan show?
The plans will show the redevelopment strategies, the existing conditions, and so on and so forth.
It will be slightly different than the sector plan.
The sector plan, like I said, will identify the infrastructure needs to handle the new development,
While the neighborhood plan will identify the efficiency in the infrastructure in terms of redevelopment.
Well, you mentioned infrastructure.
Is that just one example?
That's one example.
That could be sewer line, water line, street.
Yeah, but I know what infrastructure is.
But what about things other than infrastructure?
We will also identify that.
We will try to study the housing conditions.
We will study the social conditions of the area.
It will be a complete plan now.
And transportation.
Transportation.
Land use configuration.
Land use configuration.
Both of them.
These will all be elements.
All be elements of both reports, but will be looked at from a different angle, so to speak.
We do have in the policy manual a...
table of contents for each of the reports that we have for each kind of the report that we're going to do.
The neighborhood plan report or the sector plan report.
And it's all identified in the policy menu.
I would like for you to review it and maybe give me some comments.
from the academic... You don't know what you're saying.
We welcome all comments, but we would take that easily.
Yes, I know.
Okay, the sector planning process has come to a point where we have divided the sector and make a sector plan report.
Here's a copy.
What it is, is because the way we have

publicize this planning process, it has become a very visible type of situation and we want to make sure all along the planning process, everything we do is out in the open with the citizens of Houston so that they have a chance to comment on it.
Now also in the... That's a departure in itself.
That's a major departure.
Yes.
And I think it's probably good for the
If we want to develop some plan that will be accepted, I think we have to be involved with the residents and whatever people.
Secret planning is never successful.
Right.
And in our planning policy manual, we also have identified the procedures, how we're going to do each plan.
We have a critical path chart made up
We have identified that there will be at least two public hearings on location.
In each of the sectors.
In each of the sectors.
And we will also involve a group called Technical Advisory Committee, which is made up of professional people who may or may not live in the area.
This group, for example, are AIA, APA, ASCM, who have some general expertise of what
city's development and growth and planning is all about and should they have their own individual as a group idea of how it should be carried out.
You get a lot of free advice that way.
Well, we get a lot of free advice and we also have, when we get done, we will also have a lot of concurrence from these people to support the plans.
Oh, absolutely.
They're providing you technical advice.
If we don't, we would have to justify why we don't.
And if we do it, we also have to justify within ourselves why we take that.
We also have formed a staff task force.
This is the technical task force within all the departments of the City of Houston and some of the governmental agencies.
in this metropolitan area.

We will be calling our people like the flood control district, county engineer's office, HGAC, total authority, highway department, all the people that could provide us with technical expertise and are out there maybe doing their own long-term
plans, so to speak.
The highway department has a 20-year plan.
I just picked up something from them so that we would incorporate all this and chat with them as we go along in doing this plan.
We will have a public hearing at the very beginning to tell the residents of the area that we're coming out to do a plan for this area.
We want their support.
We want their comments and review, and we will be getting back to them either as a group.
We call them

neighborhood-based association this could be the civic organizations or the area association which is the developers organization or as individual interested individuals who will maintain contact with them all along and we have identified a planning time period of maybe 18 to 20 months for each of the plans which is a ambitious
timetable when you think of all these public meetings that we have to go through, but I think if we do it right, we could probably get done.
So, and also... You said there are 23?
There are 23 of them.
We are in the process of hiring professionals to be the project planner for each one of these, but we don't anticipate going to work on all 23.
We would probably stagger them, and we would say for 18 months for each plane, it might take us as much as four to five years to complete all 23.
That sounds reasonable.
We don't want to, you know, yeah.
We want to make sure that what we're doing is reasonable.
And also, when we get all this, you call it puzzle type of,
When we get all these pieces of puzzle put together.
Cut and paste.
Cut and paste.
I'd rather say puzzle.
It's a mystery.
But when we get all done, we will have an entire picture together.

And part of the reason we wanted to do summary plans is we know that for certain elements of planning, such as transportation, parks and recreation, you almost have to bring it back together, the whole piece for the region.
You want to make sure that when you go through one sector to another, it's in line and continuous.
But in general, you still want to look at the picture in one piece of document.
Well, I think that any legislative body insists on it eventually.
Right.
So we do see that as the next step, so to speak.
As soon as we finish the sectors and the neighborhoods,
We will be, if we have the luxury of extra staff, we might start that process early.
Now the economic condition of the city did put a crunch to our dream.
Mayor Whitmer said she's going to do some more firing.
Hopefully we'll not involve any planning department personnel unless it's really a bad person, a bad employee.
Well, you don't have any of those.
Now that we've gone through your process, I think we've pretty well finished with that, haven't we?
Yeah.
Okay.
It's my understanding that Ephraim is being criticized currently for not spending federal dollars quickly enough.
And this is probably unfair criticism.
Would you care to comment on that?
We inherited an office at the mayor's office that has not been 100% efficient, so to speak.
Which office was that?
The Climate Development.
Oh, yeah.
Okay, and they were having problems.
In fact, before we inherited, there was lawsuits against the director of the office and so on and so forth.
Lawsuits?
Well... What's her name?
Was even indicted.
Later on was taken off.
She was... You didn't know about Audie?
No, I don't think so.
Well, we could probably talk about those later on, but...
But we inherited a department that is problem-ridden, that has not been able to spend all the CD money, so to speak, on projects.
And as time goes on, the HUD offices were looking at what year money we haven't spent and how much money we have spent currently and all that.
And they discovered that we have so many that's
data back as far as three, four years ago that haven't been spent.
And I guess to teach us a lesson, they want to come back and say, well, if you can't spend it, you don't deserve it.
That doesn't go over well with the legislative body.
It never goes over well with the legislative body when that happens.
Whether it's a dollar or a million dollars.
So Ephraim has to answer some questions.
Yes.
Well, that's what he's paid for, isn't it?
Yes.
Personally, I think through the planning department, through the year of Mayor Welch and the directorship of Roscoe Jones has regressed

I wouldn't, I don't want to use the word deteriorated, but regressed in our function, okay, and maybe also because of the public works department had taken a lot of the responsibility away from us with a strong director in the person of the
You can put it in the transcript.
Anyway, so that's the situation.
I think we now are having a hard time to recapture some of the traditional planning functions that the planning department should carry out.
Let me ask you one question that I've never been clear about.
How does the city of Houston administer deed restrictions between private property owners and private parties?
Is the city a party to any of those agreements?
The city is not a party to any of those agreements.
However, the city is ready to assist any citizen groups that might have problems with

somebody within their group so to speak violating the restriction the legal department has provided legal assistance to the neighborhood associations who want to administer the restriction the planning department has provided technical support in studying the situation and reporting back to the legal department
We will not initiate any action here without requests from the citizens.
Another question.
The subject of transfer of development rights, could you elaborate a little bit on that as it's practiced in Houston?
The only transfer of development right that I can think of
is the transfer of sewer capability.
Sewer connection.
Sewer connection, okay.
Sewer availability.
That is the result of having restrictions in the capacities in the treatment plant in the general Houston area.
And so it was identified that within a sewer district, we have so much capacity
And this capacity is distributed to the vacant land or being purchased by the vacant land owners, so to speak, when they put in a certain development of sewer capacity money.
I think it's $1.86 a gallon or something like that at one time.
When we were really doing high growth, I don't think now there's a problem.
Also, because a lot of the expansion and new treatment plants are coming online that we don't have, we have a slowdown in development.
We have an increase of capacity.
So it's not a problem.
But the transfer development is really about the sewer capacity.
For a while, there was quite a business going in the purchase and sale of sewer connections.
That's what I heard.
That's what I heard also.
It was becoming quite a game in town.
Joe, when the plan is completed in four or five or however many years, then how do you anticipate it's being implemented?
Part of the cell that we are doing for the

sector plan is that when we identify problems and identify solutions to that we will add that physical solution if it's for example like a street improvement we will make recommendations to the capital improvement committee we identify it in the plan

And it's part of the idea from Ephraim that any project that's identified by this plan that's finally accepted by the planning commissioner and endorsed by the planning commissioner and accepted by the city council.
We will go through all this.
In fact, we'll let our transmitters and all that.
It will be similar to a

planning document from any other yeah well let's assume the plan has been adopted by the city council right and then what so the project that's identified in the plan would be pulled out and recommended to the capital improvement committee for action now there are three or four ways that projects can get into the capital
Well, Capital Improvement Committee.
Well, let's not go into that, but that would take care of the public sector.
Right.
Right.
What about the private sector?
Private sector, hopefully, that these plans will be something that they look at as far as the development of, like I said, infrastructure to support their development.
If they want to build a million square feet of office building in a certain area and we haven't identified
to them the necessary sewer capacity or street system to support that, then they might hopefully want to look at some other areas that we already have identified that kind of improvement there.
Or they can come back in and the traditional way is to say that we will help you develop this capability in that area so that we can develop our project.
That is perfectly acceptable as far as I understand it.
What if they come in with a proposal that is within the overall densities prescribed, but the use is not what the plan anticipates?
We will not identify by parcel what use will be assigned.
No, no, no.
I'm not suggesting by parcel.
I'm suggesting that the plan would probably be far more general than that.
That's correct.
I would doubt if you'd ever want to get down to the parcel.
No.
That would probably be a mistake.
Right.
But even so, even for an area, a neighborhood area and so forth, that a developer could conceivably come in with a proposal for uses that would not be even compatible with what's there now,
or with what the city has adopted.
Okay, you're on.
Okay.
What should I say to that?
I don't know.
What do you say to it?
How would the city handle a situation of an incompatible use proposal?
Hopefully we could go back and talk to them first to tell them why
We identify that as...
This would be friendly persuasion.
That's probably about the limit of that.
Now, I'm sure if we identify a wetland area or an area within a 100-year floodplain... Well, that's something else, yeah.
Let's assume this is all developable land, all level and ready to go.
Then we would probably have...
We would have no way to really stop a project at this time now.
A few years from now, I don't know, maybe there would be other legislative power that's given to us.
At least, maybe I've never given a whole lot of thought to that particular issue.
Better.
Yes.
Do you have anything like site plan review?
Yes, we have now development plan review.
You do.
But that's mainly about looking at whether it's compatible to the right-of-way lines that we have set out and so on and so forth.
Do you have any landscaping requirements?
I think there's some minimum landscaping requirements, but...
I think one of the things that we may be starting to look at is to evaluate some merits of projects.
I hate to say it, like what you call when a developer has to pay a certain amount to improve the school system, what's going on.
Or contribute to a park that's not property.
Right.
So like what's going on in Los Angeles, California area, that might be something for us to look at for the future.
Well, of course, the College Station test case certainly verified that in terms of park contributions.
And by
extension that could be done for anything that was a valid community service or facility, needed facility, which was caused by the development being constructed.
Right.

Part of the work that the data system is working on is hopefully with our METRICOM computerized database, extending it out to the ETJ would be able to do some of these kind of studies for certain projects, like anybody could come in
At a certain size, we would have some capability of looking at the impact to the neighborhood, impact to the street system, to the sewer system, and all that.
Schools.
Right, right.
Libraries.
Exactly.
Fire and police.
Exactly.
Joel, if you can think of anything else that you want to add or something you want to delete, mark it up on the transcript that we'll be mailing you as soon as I can get it transcribed.
Sure.
Thank you very much for your time.
You're welcome.
And for sharing your vast knowledge with us in this important project.
I believe that you probably have as much seniority as almost anyone in the department here now, don't you?
I have more seniority than Ephraim.
You've been here 16 years?
Since December of 72, after I graduated.
Have you given any thought to working elsewhere?
Well, at this time I think I'm landing on a project I would really want to get done.
I don't blame you.
It would take me five years to get it done.
I would stay for five years.
Sure.
It's really going to be a good project, and the key to it is how good a staff I can assemble.
Yeah, well, it sounds potentially very exciting.
Yes, exactly, and it's something that I always want to do.
Well, you've waited a long time to be able to do it.
Through the years, we have published some good reports, and I feel like at times I have done some things that is being taken, and it's rewarding.
You know, the planners don't see the fruit of their labor, so to speak, like a building from architect.
Well, that's why we have to maintain good health so we live long enough to see these things.
Yes.
Thanks very much, Joe.
Thank you.
